transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hey guys, in this tutorial, we\'re going to&nbsp; take a look at how to do crowd simulation. Here is the before and after. The original footage is a shot where a&nbsp; football player enters an empty stadium,&nbsp;&nbsp; and in the after, we add a crowd&nbsp; so that it looks cinematic. This task is composed of three steps.'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'First, we\'ll generate a background video&nbsp; with crowd VFX using a Video Generator node. Second, we will isolate the football&nbsp; player from the original shot and roughly&nbsp;&nbsp; comp it over the newly generated&nbsp; background using a Merge node.'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Third, we will render the entire&nbsp; composition using SwitchX. Set to fill mode so that it matches the&nbsp; color and tone of the original shot. Thank you to ActionVFX for&nbsp; providing this practice footage.'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s dive right in. The first step is to generate&nbsp; the background video. This is the footage we\'re going to use. Notice how there is no player in the beginning,&nbsp; but he enters the stadium as the video progresses. So, first, we\'re going to start by&nbsp; trimming this video to 238 frames.'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next, we extract the first frame. And since the stadium is empty right now,&nbsp;&nbsp; we\'re going to use Nano Banana with an&nbsp; Image Generator node to add the crowd VFX. I used the prompt "fill stadium&nbsp; with active crowds on @image1.'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I generated multiple different&nbsp; images and chose the best image. Next, we extend this single image into&nbsp; a video using an Image to Video model. I tried three different video models because&nbsp; I really didn\'t know which one would be the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'best. Seedance 2.0, Happy Horse, and Kling 3.0,&nbsp; and they all gave me slightly different results. And this one, Kling 3.0 was my best pick. For the prompt across all three video models,&nbsp; I told it to keep the entire video a static,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fixed angle tripod shot because&nbsp; I didn\'t want the camera to move. I also told it to add a massive crowd&nbsp; in a stadium filling the entire frame,&nbsp;&nbsp; and the audience is cheering and highly active.'

[02:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Don\'t introduce any players because I\'m&nbsp; only going to use this as a background,&nbsp;&nbsp; and to keep the entire style very&nbsp; photorealistic and in 4K high resolution. Look at how Seedance and Happy Horse&nbsp; also gave me very decent results. But it really depends on your preference.'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So here, I chose Kling 3.0. Now that the background plate is ready,&nbsp;&nbsp; let\'s roughly composite the football&nbsp; player on top of this video. For the Video Matte node, we use the&nbsp; select mode instead of the auto mode. Auto mode looks for objects in the very first&nbsp; frame, but our player isn\'t visible yet.'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So I use the select mode and&nbsp; open the Smart Select tool,&nbsp;&nbsp; which opens the dedicated alpha&nbsp; editor, and change the frame to 99. Here, the player is visible.'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So I simply typed "man" to&nbsp; select the football player. Once you have this mask ready,&nbsp;&nbsp; run the Video Matte node to propagate&nbsp; these results to the entire video. The man is now completely isolated&nbsp; throughout the entire video,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even though it wasn\'t shot on a green screen. To give it a more cinematic look, I used the&nbsp; Blur node to blur the video a little bit. You can adjust the slider&nbsp; based on your preference. Finally, using a Merge node, I layered the player&nbsp; video on top of the generated background video,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it\'s already starting to look pretty good. The final step is to match the color and tone. If you compare this to the original video,&nbsp;&nbsp; the generated stadium is very blue and high&nbsp; contrast, whereas the original is more neutral.'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We need to comp everything back and color grade&nbsp;&nbsp; it using SwitchX to recover&nbsp; the original tone and color. I selected a frame where both the&nbsp; stadium and player are visible from&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the original video and gave it&nbsp; to SwitchX as a reference frame. Notice how I didn\'t provide&nbsp; any alpha mask to SwitchX. Providing no alpha mask specifically tells SwitchX&nbsp;&nbsp; to keep everything in the frame&nbsp; and only relight and recolor it.'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s basically the same as using fill&nbsp; mode in our dedicated SwitchX tab. Now, if you compare it to the&nbsp; original video, the color matches,&nbsp;&nbsp; the crowd is added, and we\'ve completely&nbsp; achieved what we were looking for.'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That\'s it. The total credits used cost $15. All the assets are available at Beeble as a&nbsp; template Canvas project you can start from. I hope you guys enjoyed Canvas.'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There are more tutorials coming. Thank you.'
